story:
With treasured, loving and amazing memories of a true gentleman, Mr Robert 'Bob' Dilloway

Bob sadly passed away on the 3rd October 2020 aged 67 years.

A much loved Husband, Dad, Granddad and friend to many.

The funeral service will take place on Friday 23rd October 2020 at the Oaks Crematorium, Havant at 1.00pm.

Due to the current situation, only 30 mourners can be permitted to the service room. 

As many of you know, Bob was diagnosed with end stage Emhysema recently. It was Bob's wish that he did not go into a hospital or hospice, but to spend his remaining time at home with the family he loved. Bob and Mo were then faced with the daunting challenge of ensuring that Bob received the care he needed. At times, this seemed nearly impossible, although that all changed with the amazing support and reassurance provided by the Macmillan support nurses. They provided Bob and Mo with the support they needed to allow Bob to stay at home when the time happened.

By family request, friends and acquaintances are invited to stand at the gates and driveway to the crematorium at 12.45pm as a mark of respect as the hearse is paged into the grounds.

story: On 17th August we lost our lovely YiYi, six short, gruelling weeks after a secondary liver cancer diagnosis. In memory of YiYi, her 8 grandchildren will each complete the 10 Day 5K challenge, starting on 15th October, her birthday. We will log our km per day only after we have each completed our 5K for that day. Whilst we know this is a stretching time, any support that you can give will go towards fighting this terrible disease and we thank you in advance. Those who we love don't go away; they walk beside us every day. Unseen, unheard but always near; still missed, still loved and very dear. GB

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. Most people are aware that Olly & Elsie have just lost their amazing little Grandad suddenly to a cardiac arrest. Immediately Oliver said he would like to do something in his memory and to help raise money for  the British Heart Foundation. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help Oliver hit his target. Thanks!

story:
On the 8th October our beloved husband, father, brother, father-in-law, bampy and great bampy was sadly taken from us.

Brian Harris was not just an amazing family man, he was a true gentleman.

He loved his life and every person in his life, he loved to live his life to the fullest and was such a caring man.

Which brings me onto this donation page that I have set up in his memory.

His wish was that people made a donation however small to the British Heart Foundation as this was his chosen charity.

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Dad passed away on the 8th October aged 98. He lived a full life and was high spirited to the end. During these difficult times, we know friends and family are not able to pay their last respects due to restrictions in the number of people who are allowed to attend his funeral. In order to commemorate his life, Heather and I thought that we would try to raise some funds for a charity that was close to Dad’s heart, Guide Dogs for the Blind.

When reading Dad’s story below you will see why charities helping the blind were so important to him.

Dad’s Story

Dad was born on the 6th August 1922  into poor surroundings in Handsworth, Birmingham. Nothing unusual there you would think except that his father was blind following an industrial accident and never saw any of his four children.

Dad’s mother was a remarkable woman who stood by her fiancé and married him despite his disability. She also brought up their children and looked after him throughout their lives together. In order to help make ends meet,  she rented out rooms to three other blind people. This was not only to give those individuals a home where adapted accommodation would be difficult to come by in those days but also to provide some companionship for her husband.

Dad saw the challenges facing the blind first hand and later on how having a guide dog could have helped his father and he was also a dog lover. 

He will be delighted if more guide dogs were available to help blind people live an independent life.

Many thanks for your kind donation.

Paul and Heather

The sponsorship money you raise will make a difference. £100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.

It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

#TeamGuideDogs

This a unique platform offering young talented artists to put their work forward for a price and reach out to the wider community, in return for a small donation towards this page, we hope that this helps to increase their self confidence, build strength and courage to follow their passion and help to inspire others along the way.

story:
As many of you know my mum passed away just over a year ago. And to honour her memory (she was a keen orienteer and ran mountain marathons pretty much up to the end) and (hopefully) raise some money for charity (Cancer Research) I decided I would run a marathon before I officially got old. So the challenge was to run a marathon before my 50th birthday - which should/would/could have been a fun/interesting/painful experience.

However it has suddenly become a much more interesting proposition as almost every marathon has been cancelled due to Covid-19! Thus I am looking at the prospect of running a solo (virtual) marathon around my home area...

In support of this I have asked friends and family to help me on my marathon in a number of ways:

1. Runners or cyclists to run / cycle at a socially responsible distance from me in the later stages of the race.

2. Virtual Cheerers (is that even a word?) to phone me and provide encouragement at the later sections of the race.

3. Physical Cheerers who may also have new water bottles and/or jelly babies.

4. People who are willing to Sponsor me.

If I get enough support I may (read could be convinced) be willing to try 50k before 50!

This marathon is likely to happen April next year (not due to training time - I'm up to half marathons in my training atm so I doubt I need quite that long!!) - mostly so the weather isn't appalling and to give me time to recruit friends to help. / support...and deal with any logistics!

So Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Karen developed Breast Cancer in 2015 and underwent several bouts of chemotherapy and radiotherapy before an operation to remove a lump which had grown to 88mm.  Karen remained on chemotherapy for the rest of her life.

We were hopeful that she had shaken off this horrible disease but it returned again in April 2019.  The cancer had spread further and ultimately led to her untimely death on the 1st of October, 2020.

Karen fought courageously throughout her 6 year battle and faced every day with a smile on her face despite the pain which got progressively worse.  Her determination was demonstrated when she promised us she would return home against the odds after being given days to live at Christies.  She made it and died at home in our arms 48 hours later.

Karen was incredible woman who brought sunshine into many lives and we are incredibly proud of her.  She was a beautiful and devoted wife to me, and a supportive and loving Mum.  Thank you for being part of her life.

story:
My mom has been diagnosed with cancer for the second time in almost 4 years, she's an amazingly strong person with such an admirable positive attitude. But above all she is my mom and a fantastic nanny to her grandchildren, there aren't enough words to describe how proud I am of her or how much I adore her. My wonderful mom has T cell lymphoma which is a rare form of cancer there're only a handful of cases diagnosed a year which makes diagnosis difficult and in the coming week she will start chemotherapy for 6 months, with a stem cell transplant once treatment has finished. So, of course to help cancer research and those it may effect in the future it's a no brainer to try and raise awareness as priority and money to help find a cure for anyone who is diagnosed with cancer. Therefore I will be doing a 30 mile sponsored walk over the coming weeks. I'm hoping I can do more in coming months with social distancing in mind where others can take part too. This hits home for many people, so together I'm determined we can make a difference. Any donations would be greatly appreciated, cancer affects so many people but when it affects the person who you love with all your heart the fight becomes so much more real.



Let's make a difference 🙏



Thank you for taking to the time to read my moms story.



Lots of love



Harley

story:
Marie Curie's Summer collections have been put on hold as volunteers are currently unable to collect on the streets, in shops and public places. During this unsettling time, its critical that Marie Curie Nurses continue to provide care to families in need.

Marie Curie believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel.The right care means everything to families living with a terminal illness. 

Thanks to supporters like you, Marie Curie can be there for more families. Your donation will help support people living with a terminal illness across the UK, so thank you.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Dear All,
I have signed up to the 10k to help raise funds for Oxfam as sadly this year there were no Festivals to steward at - a source of huge funds for many years.  (Not as fit as when I ran 10km in London for Bhopal so will run/walk!)

Oxfam in Action UK & World wide:
In just 15 years, extreme poverty has been halved. 15 more years and we can end it for good.

Last Year - Over 22.2 million people reached  in 97 countries.Nearly 9 million people supported in 31 humanitarian emergencies.

SAFE, CLEAN WATER FOR ALL. RESPONDING IN EMERGENCIES. FIGHTING CLIMATE CHANGE. HEALTH & EDUCATION. WOMEN & GENDER JUSTICE.  HOLDING THE POWERFUL TO ACCOUNT.       
TACKLING THE CORONOVIRUS.
To fight coronavirus worldwide, we're hoping to support more than 17
million people with hygiene kits, clean water, soap and food. But this
pandemic is about more than just the virus itself. In Iraq we've set up a
gender helpline to help prevent violence against women during the crisis & in the cramped Rohingya camps in Bangladesh, local teams are providing hygiene training alongside clean water and sanitation, so people can protect themselves and spread the word. 

"We did not come here because we wanted aid. We came here to save our lives"

For more information search Oxfam GB

I am still deciding on my route - was thinking along the towpath from Bradford on Avon to Bath & then the bus back but in case it is pouring down I shall probably run halfway then back again & straight home for a hot shower! The 10k website says:

"It's a great way to set yourself a challenge, have some fun and get active while enjoying the physical and mental health benefits of running" I am so fortunate in many ways including being able to do this.

Every donation makes a difference. Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. I will let you know how I get on!

Best Wishes

Gill

charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Hi everyone! We are so excited to announce an event we have all been waiting for ... AN EVENING WITH DAVID NOTT!

Author of the brilliant No1 internationally best-selling book "War Doctor: Surgery On The Front Line" David Nott will be speaking about some of his experiences on the front line and you will have the opportunity to ask questions!

The event will be held on Microsoft team, so keep an eye out for the link on out Facebook Page.

We are holding this event in collaboration with Middle Eastern Society, we can't wait to see you all there! 

Here are some ways your donation can support MSF: 

  • £3 provides 312 ibuprofen tablets 
  • £10 provides measles vaccines for 21 children 
  • £15 can help 2 children recover from malnutrition 
  • £20 protects 62 people again hepatitis B 
  • £30 provides clean linen and gowns for 2 surgical operations 
  • £45 sends a doctor to a crisis zone for 1 day
title: Barts FoMSF - An Evening With David Nott
